      • forwardPort

        public static RakNet.UPnPResult forwardPort(int port)
                                     throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Forwards the specified UDP port via UPnP.

        In order for this method to work, UPnP for the router must be enabled. The way to enable this varies depending on the router. There is no guarantee this method will successfully forward the specified UDP port; as it is completely dependent on the gateway (the router in this case) to do so.

        This is not a blocking method. However, the code required to accomplish the task can up to three seconds to execute. As a result, it is encapsulated within another thread so as to prevent unnecessary blocking. If one wishes to get the result of the code, use the RakNet.UPnPResult.wasSuccessful() method found inside of RakNet.UPnPResult. A callback for when the task finishes can also be set using the RakNet.UPnPResult.onFinish(Runnable) method.

        Parameters:
        port - the port to forward.
        Returns:
        the result of the execution.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the port is not within the range of 0-65535.

As a result, it is encapsulated within another thread so as to prevent unnecessary blocking.       • getMaximumTransferUnit

        public static int getMaximumTransferUnit(java.net.InetSocketAddress address)
        Returns the maximum transfer unit of the network card with the specified address.

        This method is simply a shorthand for getMaximumTransferUnit(InetAddress), with the port of the address not being used. Instead, the InetSocketAddress.getAddress() method is called to retrieve the original InetAddress. If the address is null, no NullPointerException will be thrown as the possibility of a null value is accounted for.

        Parameters:
        address - the address. A null value will have the lowest valid maximum transfer unit be returned instead.
        Returns:
        the maximum transfer unit of the network card with the specified address, -1 if it could not be determined.
        Throws:
        java.lang.RuntimeException - if an exception is caught when determining the lowest valid maximum transfer unit size despite the safe checks put in place.

      • setMaxPacketsPerSecond

        public static void setMaxPacketsPerSecond(long maxPacketsPerSecond)
                                   throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Sets how many packets can be received in the span of a single second before an address is blocked.

        One must take caution when setting this value, as setting it to low can cause communication to become impossible.

        Parameters:
        maxPacketsPerSecond - how many packets can be received in the span of a single second before a peer is blocked.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if maxPacketsPerSecond is less than 0.
